    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. It feels a bit like they're trying to sneak extra responsibilities in there that aren't obvious at first glance. Are there any specific red flags or \"sneaky\" phrases in these types of clauses that usually indicate I'm being set up for more liability than I realize?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A classic red flag is language that uses overly broad terms like \"any and all claims,\" or phrases that make you responsible for the other party's own mistakes. If the clause doesn't clearly delineate *whose* actions caused the problem, you're in trouble, because the default assumption in aggressive contracts is that *you* are the cause.\n\nAnother sneaky phrase to watch out for is one that requires you to indemnify them for their own breach of the contract. That's like a giant, poorly constructed trapdoor, where you're expected to cover the costs even when *they* were the ones who messed up. It's almost always best practice to ensure the indemnification is mutual, or at least narrowly tailored to your specific actions.",
      "source": "target",
